{
  "texts": [
    "But is it possible to separate these events by calling the first, alone, my action?",
    "In comments following on from this passage, Davidson seems aware of the intuitive pull of answering 'no' -of the thought that the shoe-tying agent's actions are inseparable from the movements of the laces in getting tied.",
    "In our terms, the idea he wants to reject is that the basic actions involved in shoe tying constitutively depend on the movements of the laces.",
    "Of course, as Davidson concedes and many defenders of HEC would emphasise, the bodily movements involved in tying one's shoelaces typically do depend causally on feedback from the shoes and laces.",
    "It's therefore not obvious that lace-tying is something the agent does \"with his body alone […] separate from whatever else takes place\" (ibid.)."
  ]
}